Julius Baker (September 23, 1915 – August 6, 2003) was one of the foremost American orchestral flute players.
During the course of five decades he concertized with several of America's premier orchestral ensembles including the Chicago Symphony and the New York Philharmonic Orchestra.
Baker was born in Cleveland, Ohio, and at age nine started flute lessons with his Jewish-Russian immigrant father.
Baker was born in Cleveland, Ohio, and at age nine started flute lessons with his Jewish-Russian immigrant father.
Upon graduation in 1937, Baker returned to Cleveland to play second flute in the Cleveland Orchestra, conducted by Artur Rodziński, and in the section led by Maurice Sharp.

Baker also collaborated with Glenn Gould, the violinist Rafael Druian and members of the New York Philharmonic in a recording of Johann Sebastian Bach's Brandenberg Concerto No. 4 in G Major, BWV 1049.
Baker gave the first American performance with orchestra of the Ibert Flute Concerto in 1948 with the CBS Symphony, and that concert was later issued on his own label, Oxford Records.
